text: I followed this tutorial and it's working great! Thank You!  Any suggestions on how to get it to work for "Acrobot-v1"? I figured out how to get the actions updated from 2 (Left/Right) to 3 (negative torque, 0 torque, or positive torque), but the training part seems be the problem. I'm able to get a few random successes where the pendulum swings above the line. However, it seems like the training isn't working. Maybe a different type of network or network structure is needed? I've tried increasing the initial games to 100,000, playing around with the score requirement (-450 to -300 is what I tested) for the random games to start, modified the dropout a bit, etc, but all without luck.

author: @michaelturvey8658
text: For anyone arriving to this in 2022, just a note to say this series is now fairly out of date, unfortunately a lot of things have changed/updated since this series. The core concepts are still good, but to make anything work for me required a lot of research and figuring things out on my own, for example the env.step(action) used in this tutorial now returns a different data structure. Very challenging to work all this out on your own.

text: Ok, I hope i can help some of you out as I've been struggling for quite a few hours on this. From how he was able to do it back then it seems some things have changed. I can confirm this works fine. You just need a C++ compiler
